\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {The sorites dissolved: emergence across a band, with no decisive grain.} (\textbf  {A})~Relative thickness $\tau =\beta /\sigma $ on the linear $y$-axis ($0.03$ to $4$) versus the number of sub-floor grains added on the linear $x$-axis ($0$ to $142$), for an aggregate grown one unit at a time on a $12\times 12$ instance. The curve starts well above the threshold $\tau =1$ (red)---a tiny aggregate is all boundary---and descends smoothly through it; there is no single grain at which $\tau $ leaps across $1$, the content of Corollary~\ref {cor:sorites}(i). (\textbf  {B})~The same trajectory plotted as $\tau $ on the linear $y$-axis ($0.03$ to $4$) versus aggregate scale $\sigma (A_{n})$ on the linear $x$-axis ($1$ to $143$), threshold $\tau =1$ marked (red). Distinguishability is reached once $\sigma $ exceeds the boundary, across a band of positive width set by the floor, not at a point (Corollary~\ref {cor:sorites}(ii)). (\textbf  {C})~Per-step change $|\Delta \tau |$ on the linear $y$-axis ($0$ to $1.33$) versus grains added on the linear $x$-axis ($0$ to $141$). The increments are bounded and decay once the aggregate clears its boundary, so no individual sub-floor grain carries the aggregate across the threshold: the grain is silent because its own boundary is thick relative to it (Corollary~\ref {cor:sorites}(iii)). (\textbf  {D})~Three-dimensional overlay of three independent accretion orders (random orderings of the same atoms), each a curve of $\tau $ over aggregate scale $\sigma $ ($1$ to $\sim \!143$) at a fixed order-index $y$-coordinate. All three descend through the same $\tau \approx 1$ band regardless of accretion order, showing the dissolution is a property of the geometry, not of any particular sequence of additions. Viewing angle: elevation $20^{\circ }$, azimuth $-62^{\circ }$.}}{16}{figure.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:panel-sorites}{{4}{16}{\textbf {The sorites dissolved: emergence across a band, with no decisive grain.} (\textbf {A})~Relative thickness $\tau =\beta /\sigma $ on the linear $y$-axis ($0.03$ to $4$) versus the number of sub-floor grains added on the linear $x$-axis ($0$ to $142$), for an aggregate grown one unit at a time on a $12\times 12$ instance. The curve starts well above the threshold $\tau =1$ (red)---a tiny aggregate is all boundary---and descends smoothly through it; there is no single grain at which $\tau $ leaps across $1$, the content of Corollary~\ref {cor:sorites}(i). (\textbf {B})~The same trajectory plotted as $\tau $ on the linear $y$-axis ($0.03$ to $4$) versus aggregate scale $\sigma (A_{n})$ on the linear $x$-axis ($1$ to $143$), threshold $\tau =1$ marked (red). Distinguishability is reached once $\sigma $ exceeds the boundary, across a band of positive width set by the floor, not at a point (Corollary~\ref {cor:sorites}(ii)). (\textbf {C})~Per-step change $|\Delta \tau |$ on the linear $y$-axis ($0$ to $1.33$) versus grains added on the linear $x$-axis ($0$ to $141$). The increments are bounded and decay once the aggregate clears its boundary, so no individual sub-floor grain carries the aggregate across the threshold: the grain is silent because its own boundary is thick relative to it (Corollary~\ref {cor:sorites}(iii)). (\textbf {D})~Three-dimensional overlay of three independent accretion orders (random orderings of the same atoms), each a curve of $\tau $ over aggregate scale $\sigma $ ($1$ to $\sim \!143$) at a fixed order-index $y$-coordinate. All three descend through the same $\tau \approx 1$ band regardless of accretion order, showing the dissolution is a property of the geometry, not of any particular sequence of additions. Viewing angle: elevation $20^{\circ }$, azimuth $-62^{\circ }$}{figure.4}{}}
