\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Non-return and cessation: the record only grows, and inquiry rationally halts.} (\textbf  {A})~Committed record $M$ on the linear $y$-axis ($4$ to $378$) versus process step on the linear $x$-axis ($0$ to $60$). The record is monotone non-decreasing along the whole separation process, and the final marked point is an attempted ``undo'' that nonetheless increments $M$---the content of Theorem~\ref {thm:nonreturn}: a step intended to reverse a commitment is itself a committed step, so no traversal returns the record to a prior value. (\textbf  {B})~The cost $g(t)=-\log t$ on the linear $y$-axis ($\sim \!0.12$ to $12.6$) versus separator thickness $t$ on a logarithmic $x$-axis ($\sim \!3.5\times 10^{-6}$ to $0.89$), reproducing the divergence of Theorem~\ref {thm:cost} on the instance used for cessation. (\textbf  {C})~Marginal return per unit cost on the linear $y$-axis ($\sim \!8$ to $869$) versus thickness $t$ on a logarithmic $x$-axis (same range), with several halting thicknesses $\beta _{\ast }=e^{-\mu (\Omega )/\theta }$ marked (red) for thresholds $\theta \in \{0.5,1,2,4\}$. Because the return is bounded by $\mu (\Omega )<\infty $ while the cost diverges, the marginal return falls toward zero and a finite agent with any positive cost-per-return threshold halts at a strictly positive $\beta _{\ast }$ (Theorem~\ref {thm:cessation}). (\textbf  {D})~Three-dimensional surface of marginal return per cost over $\log _{10}t$ ($\sim \!-5.4$ to $-0.05$) and threshold $\theta $ ($0.5$ to $4$), viridis colourmap. The surface falls to a low plateau as $t\to 0$ for every $\theta $: the diverging-cost, bounded-return economy forces a halt across the whole range of thresholds, no agent driving the separator to zero. Viewing angle: elevation $24^{\circ }$, azimuth $-58^{\circ }$.}}{24}{figure.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:panel-nonreturn-cessation}{{6}{24}{\textbf {Non-return and cessation: the record only grows, and inquiry rationally halts.} (\textbf {A})~Committed record $M$ on the linear $y$-axis ($4$ to $378$) versus process step on the linear $x$-axis ($0$ to $60$). The record is monotone non-decreasing along the whole separation process, and the final marked point is an attempted ``undo'' that nonetheless increments $M$---the content of Theorem~\ref {thm:nonreturn}: a step intended to reverse a commitment is itself a committed step, so no traversal returns the record to a prior value. (\textbf {B})~The cost $g(t)=-\log t$ on the linear $y$-axis ($\sim \!0.12$ to $12.6$) versus separator thickness $t$ on a logarithmic $x$-axis ($\sim \!3.5\times 10^{-6}$ to $0.89$), reproducing the divergence of Theorem~\ref {thm:cost} on the instance used for cessation. (\textbf {C})~Marginal return per unit cost on the linear $y$-axis ($\sim \!8$ to $869$) versus thickness $t$ on a logarithmic $x$-axis (same range), with several halting thicknesses $\beta _{\ast }=e^{-\mu (\Omega )/\theta }$ marked (red) for thresholds $\theta \in \{0.5,1,2,4\}$. Because the return is bounded by $\mu (\Omega )<\infty $ while the cost diverges, the marginal return falls toward zero and a finite agent with any positive cost-per-return threshold halts at a strictly positive $\beta _{\ast }$ (Theorem~\ref {thm:cessation}). (\textbf {D})~Three-dimensional surface of marginal return per cost over $\log _{10}t$ ($\sim \!-5.4$ to $-0.05$) and threshold $\theta $ ($0.5$ to $4$), viridis colourmap. The surface falls to a low plateau as $t\to 0$ for every $\theta $: the diverging-cost, bounded-return economy forces a halt across the whole range of thresholds, no agent driving the separator to zero. Viewing angle: elevation $24^{\circ }$, azimuth $-58^{\circ }$}{figure.6}{}}
\newlabel{fig:panel-nonreturn-cessation@cref}{{[figure][6][]6}{[1][23][]24}{}{}{}}
